'''Process‚Äìarchitecture-optimization''' is a processor development model adopted in 2016 by [[Intel]]. Under this three-phase model, every [[die shrink]] is followed by a [[microarchitecture]] change and then by an optimizaton. It replaced the two-phase [[Tick‚Äìtock model]], adopted by Intel in 2006, because according to Intel the previous model is no longer sustainable.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.anandtech.com/show/10183/intels-tick-tock-seemingly-dead-becomes-process-architecture-optimization|title=Intel‚Äôs ‚ÄòTick-Tock‚Äô Seemingly Dead, Becomes ‚ÄòProcess-Architecture-Optimization‚Äô|first=Ian|last=Cutress|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eteknix.com/intel-ditches-tick-tock-for-process-architecture-optimization/|title=Intel Ditches 'Tick-Tock' for 'Process-Architecture-Optimization' - eTeknix|first=|last=eTeknix.com|date=23 March 2016|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legitreviews.com/intel-tick-tock-processor-model-replaced-process-architecture-optimization_180140|title=Intel Tick-Tock Processor Model Replaced With Process-Architecture-Optimization - Legit Reviews|date=23 March 2016|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tomshardware.com/reviews/intel-7th-gen-core-kaby-lake-preview,4728-6.html|title=Intel 7th Gen Core: Process Architecture Optimization|date=30 August 2016|publisher=}}</ref>
